# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: network-firewall-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] An **application-level gateway** (**ALG**, also known as **application-layer gateway**, **application gateway**, **application proxy**, or **application-level proxy**) is a security component that augments a firewall or NAT employed in a mobile network.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] It allows customized NAT traversal filters to be plugged into the gateway to support address and port translation for certain application layer "control/data" protocols such as FTP, BitTorrent, SIP, RTSP, file transfer in IM applications.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] In order for these protocols to work through NAT or a firewall, either the application has to know about an address/port number combination that allows incoming packets, or the NAT has to monitor the control traffic and open up port mappings (*firewall pinholes*) dynamically as required.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] Legitimate application data can thus be passed through the security checks of the firewall or NAT that would have otherwise restricted the traffic for not meeting its limited filter criteria.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] Deep packet inspection of all the packets handled by ALGs over a given network makes this functionality possible.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] An ALG understands the protocol used by the specific applications that it supports.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] For instance, for Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Back-to-Back User agent (B2BUA), an ALG can allow firewall traversal with SIP.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] If the firewall has its SIP traffic terminated on an ALG then the responsibility for permitting SIP sessions passes to the ALG instead of the firewall.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] An ALG can solve another major SIP headache: NAT traversal.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] Basically a NAT with a built-in ALG can rewrite information within the SIP messages and can hold address bindings until the session terminates.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] A SIP ALG will also handle SDP in the body of SIP messages (which is used ubiquitously in VoIP to set up media endpoints), since SDP also contains literal IP addresses and ports that must be translated.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] It is common for SIP ALG on some equipment to interfere with other technologies that try to solve the same problem, and various providers recommend turning it off.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] An ALG is very similar to a proxy server, as it sits between the client and real server, facilitating the exchange.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] There seems to be an industry convention that an ALG does its job without the application being configured to use it, by intercepting the messages.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] A proxy, on the other hand, usually needs to be configured in the client application.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] The client is then explicitly aware of the proxy and connects to it, rather than the real server.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] The *Application Layer Gateway* service in Microsoft Windows provides support for third-party plugins that allow network protocols to pass through the Windows Firewall and work behind it and Internet Connection Sharing.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] ALG plugins can open ports and change data that is embedded in packets, such as ports and IP addresses.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] Windows Server 2003 also includes an ALG FTP plugin.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] The ALG FTP plugin is designed to support active FTP sessions through the NAT engine in Windows.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] To do this, the ALG FTP plugin redirects all traffic that passes through the NAT and that is destined for port 21 (FTP control port) to a private listening port in the 3000–5000 range on the Microsoft *loopback adapter*.
[src:network-firewall-deep/application-level-gateway] The ALG FTP plugin then monitors/updates traffic on the FTP control channel so that the FTP plugin can plumb port mappings through the NAT for the FTP data channels.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] In computing, a **firewall** is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on configurable security rules.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] A firewall typically establishes a barrier between a trusted network and an untrusted network, such as the Internet or between several VLANs.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Firewalls can be categorized as network-based or host-based.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The term *firewall* originally referred to a wall to confine a fire within a line of adjacent buildings.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Later uses refer to similar structures, such as the metal sheet separating the engine compartment of a vehicle or aircraft from the passenger compartment.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The term was applied in the 1980s to network technology that emerged when the Internet was fairly new in terms of its global use and connectivity.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The predecessors to firewalls for network security were routers used in the 1980s.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Because they already segregated networks, routers could filter packets crossing them.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Before it was used in real-life computing, the term appeared in John Badham's 1983 computer‑hacking movie *WarGames*, spoken by the bearded and bespectacled programmer named Paul Richter, which possibly inspired its later use.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] One of the earliest commercially successful firewall and network address translation (NAT) products was the PIX (Private Internet eXchange) Firewall, invented in 1994 by Network Translation Inc., a startup founded and run by John Mayes.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The PIX Firewall technology was coded by Brantley Coile as a consultant software developer.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Recognizing the emerging IPv4 address depletion problem, they designed the PIX to enable organizations to securely connect private networks to the public internet using a limited number of registered IP addresses.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The innovative PIX solution quickly gained industry acclaim, earning the prestigious "Hot Product of the Year" award from Data Communications Magazine in January 1995.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Cisco Systems, seeking to expand into the rapidly growing network security market, subsequently acquired Network Translation Inc. in November 1995 to obtain the rights to the PIX technology.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The PIX became one of Cisco's flagship firewall product lines before eventually being succeeded by the Adaptive Security Appliance (ASA) platform introduced in 2005.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Firewalls are categorized as a network-based or a host-based system.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Network-based firewalls are positioned between two or more networks, typically between the local area network (LAN) and wide area network (WAN), their basic function being to control the flow of data between connected networks.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] They are either a software appliance running on general-purpose hardware, a hardware appliance running on special-purpose hardware, or a virtual appliance running on a virtual host controlled by a hypervisor.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Firewall appliances may also offer non-firewall functionality, such as DHCP or VPN services.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Host-based firewalls are deployed directly on the host itself to control network traffic or other computing resources.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] This can be a daemon or service as a part of the operating system or an agent application for protection.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The first reported type of network firewall is called a packet filter which inspects packets transferred between computers.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The firewall maintains an access-control list which dictates what packets will be looked at and what action should be applied, if any, with the default action set to silent discard.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Three basic actions regarding the packet consist of a silent discard, discard with Internet Control Message Protocol or TCP reset response to the sender, and forward to the next hop.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Packets may be filtered by source and destination IP addresses, protocol, or source and destination ports.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The first paper published on firewall technology was in 1987 when engineers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) developed filter systems known as packet filter firewalls.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] At AT&T Bell Labs, Bill Cheswick and Steve Bellovin continued their research in packet filtering and developed a working model for their own company based on their original first-generation architecture.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] In 1992, Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson released a paper on BSD Packet Filter (BPF) while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] From 1989 to 1990, three colleagues from AT&T Bell Laboratories, Dave Presotto, Janardan Sharma, and Kshitij Nigam, developed the second generation of firewalls, calling them circuit-level gateways.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard released an application firewall known as Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) in October 1993.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] This became the basis for Gauntlet firewall at Trusted Information Systems.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The key benefit of application layer filtering is that it can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port, or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] It can also provide unified security management including enforced encrypted DNS and virtual private networking.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Endpoint-based application firewalls function by determining whether a process should accept any given connection.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Application firewalls filter connections by examining the process ID of data packets against a rule set for the local process involved in the data transmission.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Application firewalls accomplish their function by hooking into socket calls to filter the connections between the application layer and the lower layers.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Application firewalls that hook into socket calls are also referred to as socket filters.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] At the core of a firewall's operation are the policies that govern its decision-making process.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] These policies, collectively known as firewall rules, are the specific guidelines that determine the traffic allowed or blocked across a network's boundaries.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Firewall rules are based on the evaluation of network packets against predetermined security criteria.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] A network packet, which carries data across networks, must match certain attributes defined in a rule to be allowed through the firewall.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Zones are logical segments within a network that group together devices with similar security requirements.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] By partitioning a network into zones, such as "Technical", "WAN", "LAN", "Public," "Private," "DMZ", and "Wireless," administrators can enforce policies that control the flow of traffic between them.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Each zone has its own level of trust and is governed by specific firewall rules that regulate the ingress and egress of data.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] A typical default is to allow all traffic from LAN to WAN, and to drop all traffic from WAN to LAN.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] In networking terms, services are specific functions typically identified by a network port and protocol.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Common examples include HTTP/HTTPS (web traffic) on ports 80 and 443, FTP (file transfer) on port 21, and SMTP (email) on port 25.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Services are the engines behind the applications users depend on.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] From a security aspect, controlling access to services is crucial because services are common targets for exploitation.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Firewalls employ rules that stipulate which services should be accessible, to whom, and in what context.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] For example, a firewall might be configured to block incoming FTP requests to prevent unauthorized file uploads but allow outgoing HTTPS requests for web browsing.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Applications refer to the software systems that users interact with while on the network.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] They can range from web browsers and email clients to complex database systems and cloud-based services.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] In network security, applications are important because different types of traffic can pose varying security risks.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Thus, firewall rules can be crafted to identify and control traffic based on the application generating or receiving it.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] By using application awareness, firewalls can allow, deny, or limit traffic for specific applications according to organizational policies and compliance requirements, thereby mitigating potential threats from vulnerable or undesired applications.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Application can both be a grouping of services, or a L7 inspection.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Implementing firewall rules based on IP addresses alone is often insufficient due to the dynamic nature of user location and device usage.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] User ID will be translated to an IP address.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] This is where the concept of "User ID" makes a significant impact.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] User ID allows firewall rules to be crafted based on individual user identities, rather than just fixed source or destination IP addresses.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] This enhances security by enabling more granular control over who can access certain network resources, regardless of where they are connecting from or what device they are using.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] The User ID technology is typically integrated into firewall systems through the use of directory services such as Active Directory, LDAP, RADIUS or TACACS+.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] These services link the user's login information to their network activities.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] By doing this, the firewall can apply rules and policies that correspond to user groups, roles, or individual user accounts instead of purely relying on the network topology.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Consider a school that wants to restrict access to a social media server from students.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] They can create a rule in the firewall that utilises User ID information to enforce this policy.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] User Identification — The firewall maps network traffic to specific user IDs by interpreting authentication logs.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] When a user logs on, the firewall associates that login with the user's IP address.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Define User Groups — Within the firewall's management interface, define user groups based on the directory service.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] For example, create groups such as "Students".
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] With this setup, only users who authenticate and are identified as members of "Students" are denied to access social media servers.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] All other traffic, starting from LAN interfaces, will be allowed.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Setting up a firewall is a complex and error-prone task.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] A network may face security issues due to configuration errors.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Firewall policies are typically configured according to the type of network in use, such as public or private environments.
[src:network-firewall-deep/firewall-computing] Administrators define rules that permit or restrict traffic in order to reduce exposure to threats like unauthorized access, malware, or other forms of cyberattack.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] When a cyber-criminal gains unauthorized access to a network, segmentation or “zoning” can provide effective controls to limit further movement across the network.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] For example separating the network for Payment Card authorizations from those for Point-of-Service (till) or customer Wi-Fi traffic.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] A sound security policy entails segmenting the network into multiple zones, with varying security requirements, and rigorously enforcing the policy on what is allowed to move from zone to zone.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] Finance and Human Resources typically need access via their own VLAN to their application servers because of the confidential nature of the information they process and store.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] Other groups of personnel may require their own segregated networks, such as server administrators, security administration, managers and executives.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] Third parties are usually required to have their own segments, with different administration passwords to the main network, to avoid attacks via a compromised, less well protected, third party site.
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] Segregation is typically achieved by a combination of firewalls and VLANs (virtual local area networks).
[src:network-firewall-deep/network-segmentation] Software-defined networking (SDN) can allow the creation and management of micro-segmented networks.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] The process, which results in the proxy server responding with its own MAC address to an ARP request for a different IP address for proxying purposes, is sometimes referred to as *publishing*.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] The access router gives the dial-up nodes IP addresses in the range 192.168.0.128 – 192.168.0.254; for this example, assume a dial-up node gets IP address 192.168.0.254.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] without being wired into the Ethernet: the access router 'publishes' its own MAC address for 192.168.0.254.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] Now, when another node wired into the Ethernet wants to talk to the dial-up node, it will ask on the network for the MAC address of 192.168.0.254 and find the access router's MAC address.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] It will therefore send its IP packets to the access router, and the access router will know to pass them on to the particular dial-up node.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] All dial-up nodes therefore appear to the wired Ethernet nodes as if they are wired into the same Ethernet subnet.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] Certain applications may require multiple IP addresses on the server.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] Provided the addresses have to be from the 10.0.0.0/24 range, the way the problem is solved is through proxy ARP.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] /other virtual server environments) and 'published' on the 10.0.0.2 interface (although many operating systems allow direct allocation of multiple addresses to one interface, thus eliminating the need for such workarounds).
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] In this scenario a firewall can be configured with a single IP address.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] One simple example of a use for this would be placing a firewall in front of a single host or group of hosts on a subnetwork.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] A proxy ARP firewall can be placed in front of the server.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] In this way the server is put behind a firewall without having to make any further changes to the network.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] Disadvantage of proxy ARP include scalability as ARP resolution by a proxy is required for every device routed in this manner, and reliability, as no fallback mechanism is present, and masquerading can be confusing in some environments.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can create DoS attacks on networks if misconfigured.
[src:network-firewall-deep/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can hide device misconfigurations, such as a missing or incorrect default gateway.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] In computing, a **stateful firewall** is a network-based firewall that individually tracks sessions of network connections traversing it.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] **Stateful packet inspection**, also referred to as dynamic packet filtering, is a security feature often used in non-commercial and business networks.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] A stateful firewall keeps track of the state of network connections, such as TCP streams, UDP datagrams, and ICMP messages, and can apply labels such as *LISTEN*, *ESTABLISHED*, or *CLOSING*.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] State table entries are created for TCP streams or UDP datagrams that are allowed to communicate through the firewall in accordance with the configured security policy.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] Once in the table, all *RELATED* packets of a stored session are streamlined, taking fewer CPU cycles than standard inspection.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] Related packets are also permitted to return through the firewall even if no rule is configured to allow communications from that host.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] If no traffic is seen for a specified time (time-out implementation dependent), the connection is removed from the state table.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] This can lead to applications experiencing unexpected disconnects or half-open TCP connections.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] Applications can be written to send keepalive messages periodically to prevent a firewall from dropping the connection during periods of no activity or for applications which by design have long periods of silence.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] The method of maintaining a session's state depends on the transport protocol being used.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] TCP is a connection-oriented protocol and sessions are established with a three-way handshake using *SYN* packets and ended by sending a *FIN* notification.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] The firewall can use these unique connection identifiers to know when to remove a session from the state table without waiting for a timeout.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] UDP is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not send unique connection-related identifiers while communicating.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] Because of that, a session will only be removed from the state table after the configured time-out.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] UDP hole punching is a technology that leverages this trait to allow for dynamically setting up data tunnels over the internet.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] ICMP messages are distinct from TCP and UDP and communicate control information of the network itself.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] A well-known example of this is the ping utility.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] ICMP responses will be allowed back through the firewall.
[src:network-firewall-deep/stateful-firewall] In some scenarios, UDP communication can use ICMP to provide information about the state of the session so ICMP responses related to a UDP session will also be allowed back through.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] A **next-generation firewall** (**NGFW**) is a part of the third generation of firewall technology, combining a conventional firewall with other network device filtering functions, such as an application firewall using in-line deep packet inspection (DPI) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS).
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Other techniques might also be employed, such as TLS-encrypted traffic inspection, website filtering, QoS/bandwidth management, antivirus inspection, third-party identity management integration (e.g.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] LDAP, RADIUS, Active Directory), and SSL decryption.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] **Unified Threat Management** refers to a similar appliance as an NGFW.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] One of the first mentions of the NGFW term was in a 2004 document by Gartner.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Kenneth Tam speculated that the term Unified Threat Management (UTM) was coined by IDC because they did not want to adopt the name of their competitor.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] NGFWs include the typical functions of traditional firewalls such as packet filtering, network- and port-address translation (NAT), stateful inspection, and virtual private network (VPN) support.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] The goal of next-generation firewalls is to include more layers of the OSI model, improving filtering of network traffic that is dependent on the packet contents.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] The most significant differences are that NGFWs include intrusion prevention systems (IPS) and application control.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Next-generation firewalls perform deeper inspection compared to stateful inspection performed by the first- and second-generation firewalls.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] NGFWs use a more thorough inspection style, checking packet payloads and matching signatures for harmful activities such as exploitable attacks and malware.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Modern threats like web-based malware attacks, targeted attacks, application-layer attacks, and more have had a significantly negative effect on the threat landscape.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] In fact, one in four attacks exploit vulnerabilities in public-facing applications, as opposed to weaknesses in networking components and services.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Stateful firewalls with simple packet filtering capabilities were efficient blocking unwanted applications as most applications met the port-protocol expectations.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Administrators could promptly prevent an unsafe application from being accessed by users by blocking the associated ports and protocols.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] But blocking a web application that uses port 80 by closing the port would also mean complications with the entire HTTP protocol.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Protection based on ports, protocols, IP addresses is no more reliable and viable.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] This has led to the development of identity-based security approach, which takes organizations a step ahead of conventional security appliances which bind security to IP-addresses.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] NGFWs offer administrators a deeper awareness of and control over individual applications, along with deeper inspection capabilities by the firewall.
[src:network-firewall-deep/unified-threat-management] Administrators can create very granular "allow/deny" rules for controlling use of websites and applications in the network.
